<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880709-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
preliminary figures from mexicos 
presidential election show the ruling institutional revolutionary 
party candidate winning but with the lowest margin in its six 
decades in office 
federal electoral commission figures obtained from a reliable 
source show carlos salinas de gortari with 474 percent of the 45 
million votes counted so far cuauhtemoc cardenas of the leftist 
national democratic front was second with 267 percent and manuel 
j clouthier of the conservative national action party third with 
207 percent 
the 45 million votes counted are out of 117 million ballots 
reported so far to the commission mexico has 38 million registered 
voters but no figures are available how many voted in wednesdays 
election 
in addition to the presidency 64 senate seats and 500 in the 
newly expanded chamber of deputies are at stake 
a final vote count is not expected until sunday the early leak 
appeared designed to counter growing speculation that the ruling 
party known as the pri for its initials in spanish had suffered a 
devastating loss 
jorge de la vega dominguez chairman of the pri proclaimed a 
party victory in at least 27 of mexicos 31 states and said 
opposition accusations of fraud were meant to confuse the 
electorate 
the pri is going to defend its legal and unobjectionable 
electoral triumph with all the means of the law it is going to 
mobilize the force of all its organizations to combat the 
provocation and irresponsibility of the opposition he said 
a relaxed and smiling salinas meeting friday night with foreign 
reporters insisted that he was more concerned that the vote count 
be credible than with his margin of victory 
those results reflect real votes he said the results so 
far ratify this circumstance of plurality and a new political 
reality in mexico 
he said opposition parties will be most visible in the chamber 
of deputies where presumably would have a role in approving or 
blocking constitutional changes that require a twothirds majority 
at a news conference earlier friday clouthier accused the 
government of delaying an announcement in order to falsify results 
they are waiting to see how to disguise the figures he said 
i believe we won but i dont want to boast prematurely as my 
adversary has he said of the victory claim by salinas de 
gortari mexico has changed totally changed we will never 
have only one party again 
clouthier said he and cardenas met earlier in the day and agreed 
to share their information on voting results in order to challenge 
government figures 
he said they also agreed not to release figures publicly for the 
time being because when the government finds out what information 
the opposition has then officials will know which results they can 
dress up 
no pri presidential candidate since the partys founding in 1929 
has won less than 70 percent of the vote 
the slow count also is making evident splits within the pri 
between the 40yearold salinas de gortari and the oldstyle 
politicians 
the federal electoral commission which controls the vote count 
is headed by interior secretary manuel bartlett who was among 
salinas de gortaris chief rivals for the presidential nomination 
salinas de gortari has insisted throughout the campaign that he 
will introduce a new era in which opposition voices will be heard 
cardenas a former pri governor in the central state of 
michoacan until his break with the pri last year waged an 
unusually strong campaign that capitalized on widespread discontent 
with the hardships caused by six years of economic crisis 
the leftist candidate is the son of the revered late president 
lazaro cardenas in renouncing his own presidential hopes and 
endorsing cardenas last spring heberto castillo of the rival 
mexican socialist party described the cardenas movement as a 
phenomenon 
salinas de gortari appeared ready to concede losses to cardenas 
in michoacan the central state of morelos and in the federal 
district the core of the sprawling mexico city metropolitan area 
a fourth cardenas victory could come in the populous state of 
mexico which abuts the federal district on three sides 
the vote count made available to the associated press also 
showed gumersino magana negrete of the conservative mexican 
democratic party with 095 percent of the vote and rosario ibarra 
de piedra of the radical revolutionary workers party with 04 
percent 
most districts recorded so far are urban where cardenas and 
clouthier are strongest the salinas de gortari percentage could be 
expected to rise slightly with reports from rural district where 
the pri is traditionally strong 
bartlett said soon after the election that technical 
difficulties with a new computer system delayed the returns he 
later blamed bad weather 
the government says the elections were peaceful and clean pri 
officials have said charges by opposition parties that the 
balloting was fraudulent were a publicity move 
the assembly for effective suffrage a civic watchdog group 
recorded 1100 cases of voting irregularities ranging from 
ballotstuffing to tampering with voter registration rolls 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

