<TEXT>
falling water levels on the mississippi river 
that have stranded barges are threatening to trigger a regional 
water fight on capitol hill pitting southern senators and others 
against great lakes lawmakers 
on friday sen james sasser dtenn asked president reagan 
for an emergency diversion of water from the great lakes 
sasser and 12 other senators urged reagan in a letter to direct 
the us army corps of engineers to increase the flow of great 
lakes water to the illinois waterway and the lower mississippi from 
3000 to 10000 cubic feet per second for 100 days 
the action triggered immediate opposition from several midwest 
lawmakers led by sen howard metzenbaum dohio who said it would 
be illegal unless approved by all the great lakes governors 
and in canada justice minister ray hnatyshyn told parliament 
that canadas ambassador in washington allan gotlieb would 
deliver a formal notice to the state department saying that canada 
is unalterably opposed to any diversion 
hnatyshyn said canada can veto any diversion proposal as a 
result of several treaties we control our resources he said 
we will continue to control our resources 
sasser said the drought has pushed water levels on the 
mississippi three feet lower than they have been since 1872 when 
officials first began keeping records as many as 3000 barges are 
stranded with the loss to the barge and towing industry possibly 
exceeding 60 million he said 
communities along the river face the prospects of drinking 
water shortages and drinking water pollution because of the 
drought said sasser 
he said the diversion would raise the level of the river by one 
foot in st louis and six inches in memphis and only lower the 
level of lake michigan and lake huron by one inch 
metzenbaum said the great lakes states are hurting as well he 
said great lakes water levels have fallen two feet in the past 18 
months and are likely to continue to fall 
metzenbaum also said any action to divert the water would be 
illegal because the 1986 water resources development act bars 
diversion unless it is approved by all of the great lakes governors 
also the supreme court has set a limit on how much water can be 
diverted without its permission 
sasser said he believes the president has the authority to take 
the action as commander in chief in a national emergency 
sen carl levin dmich said corps officials he has talked to 
do not believe they have the legal authority to take the action or 
that it would do much good he said they believe that reducing the 
loads of barges would be more effective 
lake levels have dropped by 30 inches in the past two years 
said sen donald riegle dmich 
added sen william proxmire dwis diversion of water from 
the great lakes into the mississippi may damage navigation 
hydroelectric generation and the environment 
signing the letter to reagan urging the diversion were sasser 
and sens albert gore dtenn dale bumpers dark david pryor 
dark mitch mcconnell rky paul simon dill john stennis 
dmiss bennett johnston dla john breaux dla wendell ford 
dky alan dixon dill john danforth rmo and christopher 
bond rmo 
others joining metzenbaum in speaking against the action were 
sens dave durenberger rminn and bob kasten rwis 
