<TEXT>
the leaders of 13 caribbean nations 
have accused the us justice department of interfering in their 
regions affairs as it cracks down on drugs and urged president 
reagan to halt the meddling 
members of caricom the caribbean community and common market 
ended five days of talks friday without agreeing on haitis coup 
but they agreed to work toward eliminating obstacles to regional 
trade by oct 1 
the leaders drafted a letter to president reagan saying that the 
us justice department was overstepping its jurisdiction by 
investigating alleged drug traffickers in panama and the caribbean 
the contents of the letter were not revealed but antigua deputy 
prime minister lester bird said it would be signed by the caricom 
secretary general to represent all the leaders 
bird announced it would protest what the leaders considered a 
derogation of their local laws and us violations of their 
sovereignty as the reagan administration seeks to win favor in an 
election year 
some of the leaders criticized bird for making the announcement 
prematurely prime minister james mitchell of st vincent and the 
grenadines said it was bad manners 
others stressed their traditionally close ties with the united 
states and said it had not intervened directly in their affairs 
bird reading from a communique drafted by the leaders said 
they also reaffirmed their total commitment to the fight against 
all illegal trafficking in drugs 
they expressed their willingness to ccoperate with other 
countries for the establishment of internationally acceptable 
mechanisms to bring offenders to justice he said 
the caribbean has long been a source and an important conduit 
for drugs coming into the united states cocaine from south america 
traditionaly passes through caribbean ports before entering the 
united states much marijuana is also grown in the area 
from the start of the meeting monday it was apparent the 
leaders were unlikely to reach unanimous agreement as required by 
caricom rules on what position to take on the haitian military 
government that ousted president leslie manigat in a coup june 19 
they debated options ranging from revoking haitis status as an 
observer on four caricom standing committees to simply issuing a 
strong statement denouncing the coup 
the leaders were more successful when talking about 
intraregional trade 
the leaders agreed to remove all trade obstacles such as stamp 
duties and import licenses by oct 1 and to study a request by the 
smaller countries to protect 23 items they consider too fragile to 
compete with imports 
trade and industry ministers will meet before the oct 1 
deadline to decide which items should be excluded and for how long 
caricom established in 1973 to promote regional trade and set 
common positions on international events includes antiguabarbuda 
bahamas barbados belize dominica grenada guyana jamaica 
montserrat st kittsnevis st lucia st vincent and the 
grenadines and trinidadtobago 
