soviet premier nikolai ryzhkov 
says the red army will withdraw from foreign lands by the end of 
the century but a us official says a soviet pullout may be 
imminent in hungary 
a state department official said friday that there are 
increasing indications of a unilateral withdrawal from hungary 
which was invaded by soviet troops in 1956 to crush an uprising 
reports of a possible soviet withdrawal have circulated for a 
year and a half the state department official who spoke on 
condition of anonymity said its information is based on us 
intelligence reports 
ryzhkov speaking to western reporters friday gave no 
indication that the soviet union was preparing a unilateral 
withdrawal from an east bloc nation before 2000 
the soviet government chief told western reporters such moves 
could come only in the context of a general withdrawal involving 
western forces as well 
he said his government feels no armies should be on foreign 
territory us british or soviet 
our proposal is this let us take out all the armies he 
said the armies in czechoslovakia are part of the warsaw pact 
armies let us agree on a radical solution in the west and in the 
east 
red army units are stationed in several soviet bloc countries 
including czechoslovakia hungary and east germany 
state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley cautioned that after 
announcing troop withdrawals form east germany in 1983 the soviets 
built their forces in that country back to the same levels within 
three years 
currently four soviet tank and motorized rifle divisions remain 
in hungary the troops are not on the front lines opposite nato 
forces however because hungary is bordered to the west by three 
warsaw pact nations and politically neutral yugoslavia and austria 
even with a withdrawal said oakley the warsaw pact would hold 
a 21 advantage over the north atlantic treaty organization in 
tanks artillery and armored personnel vehicles 
