<TEXT>
evert clark who specialized in aviation 
science and space in 40 years of reporting for publications 
including the new york times and newsweek has died he was 62 
clark who was technical news editor for business week and other 
magazines serviced by the mcgrawhill world news bureau for the 
last 10 years died thursday at montgomery general hospital in 
suburban maryland after surgery for an aneurysm 
born in gainesville ga clark began his career in journalism 
in 1947 as a reporter and editor for the durham nc morning 
herald 
he became a feature writer for the washington daily news in 1948 
before he turned his passion for aviation and space into a position 
as the first space editor for aviation week and space technology 
magazine in 1956 
he covered the us effort to land a man on the moon and was 
cited with an award by the national space club in 1969 for his 
penetrating consistently informed and lucid writing 
he joined the new york times in 1963 as an aviation and space 
reporter in 1963 and moved to newsweek in 1968 covering science 
and technology as well as the watergate breakin during his 10 
years in the magazines washington bureau he wrote a book titled 
contrabandista with newsweek colleague nicholas horrock on the 
drug trade 
clark served in the navy from 1944 to 1946 and graduated from 
the university of north carolina in 1947 he lived most recently in 
gaithersburg md 
he is survived by his wife june one son david s clark and 
two daughters kristin l dougherty and amy s bockhaus 
</TEXT>
