power for six decades 
the institutional revolutionary party has been beset by 
infighting between oldguard operatives who want to keep the system 
intact and a new breed led by presidential candidate carlos salinas 
de gortari who want to modernize the party machine 
the political system now is made up of a huge network of 
patronage and porkbarrel projects that can create or eliminate 
jobs and which provide a raft of favors to loyal party members 
corruption has been a key ingredient in its succes 
under the system the outgoing president usually names his 
successor subject to approval by the party other candidates are 
chosen in closed conventions and the party machinery makes sure 
they get elected 
the system has kept the party in power under various names since 
it was formed in 1929 its presidential candidate always has won 
with at least 70 percent of the vote 
it has held the governors offices in all of mexicos 31 states 
and lost only one senate race to a coalition that included the 
party in the chamber of deputies it has tolerated a weak 
opposition 
opponents or opposition groups who became to powerful often were 
bought off with plush jobs or gradually swallowed by the 
institutional revolutionary party 
for years it worked slowly like an amoeba assimilating and 
incorporating opposition groups one old pri hand who spoke on 
condition he not be identified said recently 
as long as mexico remained even relatively prosperous it could 
finance the partys system and the party kept mexico politically 
stable and generally content 
the bubble burst in 1982 when prices of oil mexicos 
principal export plunged bringing on one of the severest 
economic crises in half a century 
jobs suddenly were not plentiful real income plunged by at 
least 40 percent 
one of the engineers of the austerity program was salinas di 
gortari 40 a harvardeducated economist who served for five years 
as president miguel de la madrids budget and planning secretary 
the crisis also brought widespread discontent and this 
strengthened the parties both on the right and the left of the 
governing party the tensions between the old guard and the 
technocrats became more visible after salinas nomination for 
president last year 
de la madrid a harvard educated technocrat himself ignored 
objections from powerful groups and selected salinas as his 
successor 
many favored interior secretary manuel bartlett and others 
backed thenenergy and mines secretary alfredo del mazo 
fidel velazquez 88 general secretary of the partys power 
mexican labor federation and a member of the old guard made no 
bones of his displeasure when salinas de gortari was proclaimed by 
the party as its presidential candidate 
preliminary election figures from the federal electoral 
commission show the party won the presidency by its slimmest margin 
yet 
early returns indicate salinas de gortari won an estimated 474 
percent while cuauhtemoc cardenas of the leftist national 
democratic front had 267 percent and manuel j clouthier of the 
conservative national action party had 207 percent 
even before wednesdays elections salinas said in his speeches 
the party should be modernized to meet the growing challenge of the 
opposition 
the lefts apparent success in the elections was spurred by 
cardenas who broke with the governing party last year after his 
push for reforms was rebuffed 
salinas aides now speak of a multiparty system for mexico 
in which the institutional revolutionary party would occupy an 
expandable center 
salinas campaigned for democratic reforms less state 
intervention in the economy and the need for clean elections 
aides said throughout the campaign that he was prepared to 
sacrifice ideology to practicality in a bid not just to get to los 
pinos the presidential residence but to get there with some of 
his partys credibility intact 
the major question for him in his first months of office will be 
how much resistance the old guard puts up to his proposed 
changes 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note isaac a levi has been covering latin american 
for the associated press for 25 years the last 14 of them based in 
mexico city 
</TEXT>
