<TEXT>
nuclear power plants across the nation may 
have bought used circuit breakers that were falsely labeled as new 
according to documents filed in federal court by the nuclear 
regulatory commission 
the nrc is investigating five southern california companies for 
their alleged role in supplying the circuit breakers which serve 
the same function as fuses in shutting off power to prevent short 
circuits or fires 
the nrc is unsure where the breakers are being used or what 
dangers they present except that they appear prone to failure 
officials said 
after seizing documents during searches at the companies 
offices thursday the nrc sent notices friday to nuclear power 
plants across the united states 
we are advising plant operators of what we are doing but we 
are not asking them to do anything at this time said frank 
ingham an nrc spokesman in washington 
it is too early to determine the extent of the potential 
problem ingham said 
federal officials said the used breakers were first discovered 
at the diablo canyon nuclear power plant near san luis obispo when 
they failed tests there four months ago 
according to court documents the breakers that failed at diablo 
canyon were purchased for use in nonsafetyrelated areas or areas 
that are separate from a plants nuclear reactor 
however an examination of breakers seized from the five 
companies showed that it would be possible for power plant workers 
to believe that a breaker was new and to upgrade a circuit 
breaker to a safetysystem use wrote robert marsh the nrcs 
regional director of investigations 
