a portuguese newspaper reported saturday 
that 2000 cuban troops have been sent to angola to bolster 
government defenses near the border with namibia 
the independent weekly expresso quoted unidentified reliable 
sources as saying the cubans described as experts in mounting and 
firing missiles landed in the former portuguese colony in june 
the newspaper said the reinforcements were sent to strengthen 
the position of the marxist angolan government and cuba in 
negotiations with south africa and the united states to end the 
13year civil war in angola 
the reinforcements arrived shortly before a second round of 
peace negotiations between the four countries in cairo egypt the 
newspaper said lower level delegations scheduled more talks monday 
and tuesday in new york 
in a separate story expresso quoted unidentified diplomatic 
sources in havana as saying cuban forces had mounted a defensive 
line involving 26000 men in the south of angola close to south 
africanadministered namibia also known as southwest africa 
angola and cuba have acknowledged that cuba began sending 
reinforcements of elite troops to angola in november to help the 
35000 cuban soldiers already stationed there contain south african 
advances in the south 
western analysts believe those reinforcements brought the number 
of cubans in angola to about 46000 
expresso claimed the cuban reinforcements were creating 
differences between the angolan government and cuba 
last week jorge risquet the chief cuban negotiator at the 
peace talks strongly denied any rift he told a news conference in 
lisbon all military decisions were made by the angolan government 
south african troops in angola support guerrillas of the 
national union for the total independence of angola also backed by 
the united states who have been fighting since 1975 to force the 
soviet and cubansupported government to share power 
a peace settlement turns on securing a withdrawal of foreign 
troops from angola and implementing a un resolution to make 
namibia independent 
