following the 1965 riots 
the wattswillowbrook plant which makes parts for the c5 cargo 
plane will close by october when work on the c5 is completed the 
company said friday the plant is on the citys south side about 8 
miles from downtown 
of the plants 117 workers 78 have enough seniority to qualify 
for transfers to the companys burbank plant about 20 miles away 
lockheed said it will attempt to find employment for the rest with 
other aerospace firms 
a lockheed spokesman said the company had expected to use the 
plant for other work after the completion of the c5 program but 
lockheeds aircraft business has been dwindling and no suitable 
projects could be found 
we had hoped that lockheed would be able to feed more work to 
wattswillowbrook said mark molli an aide to us rep augustus 
f hawkins dcalif we want to see that the workers are taken 
care of 
former lockheed president a carl kotchian recalled in a recent 
interview that the companys decision to open the plant four years 
after the devastating riot was considered controversial 
i had my own people take issue with me kotchian said 
they said i was going to spend a lot of money and the place was 
going to be run down and there was going to be thievery and 
muggings at the plant none of it came to pass 
instead the plant matched the productivity and efficiency of 
most lockheed factories he said 
the arrest of a black man by a state highway patrol officer on 
aug 11 1965 touched off a week of rioting that turned watts into 
a national symbol of racial strife 
thirtyfour people died in the riot and 4000 people were 
arrested damage from the six days of looting fires and shooting 
reached 40 million 
dv industries a smaller aerospace company that has operated in 
watts for 30 years plans to take over lockheeds 25year lease on 
the factory which is owned by economic resources corp a 
nonprofit group formed after the riot 
the company expects to double its 55person work force over the 
next year and will give hiring preference to former lockheed 
workers said carl la barbera dvs executive vice president 
dv industries a privately held company with sales under 10 
million per year inspects and paints aircraft parts for lockheed 
boeing and other aerospace firms 
