the governing nationalist party began 
saturday to partially dismantle its oldguard leadership but it 
has yet to decide how much new blood to inject into its top ranks 
the party removed 10 of the 31 members of the policymaking 
central standing committee including five who are in their 80s 
the 10 were named to the central advisory committee an honorary 
supervisory group of mostly retired officials 
nationalist leaders have stressed the importance of promoting 
younger members of the party known as the kuomingtang which was 
formed 94 years ago on the chinese mainland and has for four 
decades claimed to be the sole rightful ruler of china 
party spokesman raymond tai told reporters that the new central 
standing committee will be named thursday at the end of the 
weeklong 13th party congress a cabinet overhaul is expected later 
most of the aging leaders in the current central standing 
committee whose members average age is 70 fled to taiwan from 
the chinese mainland in 1949 when chiang kaishek and his 
nationalist government were routed by the communists 
these older nationalists still hold a majority of seats in the 
parliament and support the partys claim that it has the right to 
govern china 
the personnel changes are likely to determine the pace for 
continuing the liberalization program started by president chiang 
chingkuo before his death in january chiang the eldest son of 
chiang kaishek lifted martial law allowed new political parties 
and eased a ban on travel to mainland china 
president lee tenghui who friday was elected the first native 
taiwanese party chairman has vowed to continue the democratic 
changes but he has moved cautiously in the past months in order to 
consolidate his power 
the new members of the advisory committee were proposed by lee 
and approved by the party congress 
three media executives on the central standing committee who 
have said they want to give way to a younger leadership also were 
named to the advisory panel 
but two influential 74yearold conservatives on the 
policymaking committee premier yu kuohwa and shen changhuan 
secretary to the president were not reassigned 
the independence evening post newspaper said saturday that yu 
and four other elder statesmen will remain a major force as the 
old generals lead the team while the young officials intern 
this will be a very conservative restructuring wrote 
political commentator antonio chiang he added that as the older 
politicians power base diminishes younger members of the party 
may be more willing to speak out 
