<TEXT>
the head of the international monetary fund 
cautioned participating banks on friday that failure to upgrade aid 
to the debtor nations would slow their financial growth 
unless the banks do more to support adjustment efforts of 
middleincome counties the notion that our debt strategy is a 
collaborative one oriented to growth will not pass serious 
scrutiny michel camdessus said 
indeed it will prevent the resumption of an adequate rate of 
growth and all sides will lose he said in a speech prepared for 
a meeting of the united nations economic and social council in 
geneva 
camdessus endorsed agreements between the debtor nations and 
creditors for new arrangements to reduce the estimated 12 
trillion debt of certain third world the nations with the largest 
debts are in latin america brazil mexico and argentina where 
us banks are the largest lenders 
he expressed concern over difficulties in developing loan 
packages for those governments trying to adjust to their 
international debt problems such packages usually include loans by 
the fund itself by commercial banks and by intergovernmental 
lenders like the world bank 
adjustments required in return for the loans generally include 
austerity programs that debtor governments find difficult 
camdessus said programs to adjust debtor countries to a better 
handling of their funds will in many cases have costs in the short 
run but will eventually help their citizens and particularly the 
poor 
the poor would almost certainly suffer much more in the 
absence of corrective action he said noting that the poor can 
be protected at least to some degree by compensatory measures 
camdessus noted that some adjustment measures are of immediate 
help to some poor people such as increased prices for farm 
products that help the poor in rural areas 
