<TEXT>
a montreal police officer who shot and killed an 
unarmed black teenager last year raising a storm of protest from 
the citys black community was fired from the force friday by 
police chief roland bourget 
bourget told reporters he accepted last months recommendation 
by a police disciplinary committee that constable allan gosset a 
16year veteran of the force be dismissed for negligence in the 
arrest and death of 19yearold anthony griffin last november 
the committee said gosset 38 pointed his gun at griffin 
without justification then fired killing him with a single 
bullet to the forehead 
gosset shot griffin outside a police station after the youth 
bolted from custody he obeyed an order to stop but was shot as he 
turned to face gosset 
gosset said the gun went off accidentally he was suspended from 
his job and charged with manslaughter an allwhite jury acquitted 
him in february but the prosecution has appealed the verdict as 
canadian law allows 
protests among montreals 120000 blacks prompted quebec justice 
minister herbert marx to order inquiries by the quebec police 
commission and human rights commission 
the police commission concluded june 9 that gosset was 
negligent thoughtless and lacking in vigilance and judgment 
but found no evidence the shooting was racially motivated both the 
commission and the police departments internal disciplinary 
committee recommended gossets dismissal 
montreal has six blacks among its 4481 police officers 
gosset and a policewoman arrested griffin after a taxi driver 
complained that a customer refused to pay a fare a identity check 
showed griffin was wanted on breaking and entering charges 
gosset and his lawyer serge menard spent two hours with 
bourget on friday in an effort to prevent the dismissal the police 
officers union the montreal police brotherhood pledged to fight 
for his reinstatement 
</TEXT>
