the united states agreed saturday to 
provide an additional 5 million to aid thai villagers living along 
the embattled borders with laos and cambodia the us embassy said 
the agreement was initialed in a ceremony by visiting us 
secretary of state george p shultz and his thai counterpart siddhi 
savetsila 
the funds to be used to help some 300000 thais in 412 
villages bring to 42 million the total amount washington has 
provided since 1980 to help the frontier villagers the embassy 
said 
the funds are to be used to construct reservoirs and irrigation 
systems rural access roads and public health facilities in the 
border area 
fighting between vietnamese and cambodian guerrilla forces 
frequently spills into thailand and border clashes between the 
thais and laotians have flared periodically since communist forces 
triumphed in that country in 1975 
