<TEXT>
consumer prices rose 413 percent for the 
first half of 1988 the business daily el financiero reported 
friday 
it tabulated the figures from the bank of mexicos announcement 
that inflation rose 2 percent in june slightly above the 19 
percent increase in may 
el financieros report noted that despite an increase in june 
figures for both months were the lowest registered since november 
1981 
inflation has been reduced by an economic solidarity pact 
designed by the government in december and endorsed by business and 
labor consumer prices hit a record 1592 percent last year 
president miguel de la madrid announced the program after 
officials became worried that mexico was on the verge of spiraling 
into hyperinflation a problem that has plagued other latin 
american countries 
critics say the pact was intended to artificially control 
inflation before wednesdays general elections 
the president concludes his sixyear term on nov 30 with his 
successor virtually certain to be carlos salinas de gortari of the 
institutional revolutionary party that has governed mexico since 
1929 
the budget and planning secretary pedro aspe said wednesday 
that it will be up to the next administration to decide if the pact 
continues past november 
he told reporters that the agreement remains in effect at least 
through august and that its status for the last three months of de 
la madrids term wont be determined until the middle of next month 
a bank of mexico report issued late thursday said a beef 
shortage in turn prompted increases in prices of chicken and pork 
and so contributed to higher prices as did a longer than usual dry 
season that caused increases in fruit and vegetable prices 
among other factors in junes consumer price rises were 
residential rents which were 43 percent higher and represented 
the largest single increase the central bank said prices on basic 
foods and other essentials rose 4 percent 
of the 35 cities checked the highest increases were 43 percent 
in zamora in western michoacan state and 25 percent in toluca 
40 miles west of mexico city 
the banks report said the solidarity pact continues being 
successful in holding down the inflationary process 
a key component of the inflationfighting program is a freeze on 
the minimum wage prices of governmentregulated goods and services 
and the exchange rate of the peso currency 
</TEXT>
