<TEXT>
after weeks of playing followthesoybeans traders in a number 
of commodity markets are looking elsewhere for signals on whether 
to buy or sell 
some of these markets such as gold and sugar have only a 
marginal interest in grain and soybean prices to begin with 
others cotton in particular have almost no real relationship 
to soybeans and are cooling down after a frantic ride on the 
drought train courtesy of market speculators 
the midwestern drought remains the dominant influence in the 
grain and soybean markets and in the livestock markets where the 
price of feed grain is directly related to production costs 
but the droughts diminishing impact on the prices of other 
commodities illustrates how the powerful psychology of a runaway 
market can sweep others along with it until the facts get in the 
way 
in the end the fundamentals always reign supreme said 
ernest simon cotton specialist with prudential bache securities 
inc in new york 
in the cotton market the fundamentals include the agriculture 
departments prediction of a 56 millionbale surplus on july 31 
the end of the current marketing year and a whopping 68 
millionbale surplus a year later there is nearly enough cotton in 
storage to fulfill all of next years expected domestic demand 
twice as much as experts consider adequate 
before the drought began the usda estimated 198889 cotton 
production at 14 million bales analysts say even severe drought 
damage wouldnt reduce the oversupply 
we could lose 2 million bales and not be hurt said ed 
whitten cotton specialist with balfour maclaine corp in new york 
so why did nearmonth cotton futures follow the soybean markets 
sharp springtime surge rallying from about 60 cents a pound on 
april 15 to almost 70 cents by june 20 
cotton very often is called soybeans little brother 
whitten said it follows it slavishly 
added rich cantor cotton analyst with merrill lynch capital 
markets inc it wasnt so much the fabulous buying that brought 
the prices up it was that you didnt have anybody willing to sell 
it that allowed the speculative element to move prices higher in 
tandem with the other markets 
cotton futures prices have since come back down to around 60 
cents a pound 
people finally became convinced the fundamentals had been 
ignored too long said simon 
the inflationsensitive gold market followed a similar albeit 
shorter path in early june gold for august delivery surged above 
its recent 440to460 trading range to more than 470 a troy 
ounce the accepted explanation was that traders feared the sharp 
rise in grain prices would lead to greater inflation 
those worries were quickly calmed by economists who pointed out 
the miniscule impact of food prices on the consumer price index 
and gold prices eased back into their wellworn trading range 
the soybean market and the rally we had in previous weeks 
certainly constituted a psychological inducement to rally the 
precious metals but in general you have to keep the advance in 
perspective said george anagnos metals analyst with thomson 
mckinnon securities inc in new york 
the gold market indicated that foodinspired increases 
alone were not going to boost inflation rates to dangerously high 
levels 
in fact commodity markets almost never take their direction 
from a single source and singleday moves often have no easy 
explanation said steve chronowitz director of futures research 
for smith barney harris upham amp co in new york 
the media naturally wants to know why gold is up a dollar 
today or why its down a dollar he said sometimes there is no 
reason but when theyre at a loss to explain a move analysts will 
tend to tie it to something else 
</TEXT>
