<TEXT>
oil futures gave up some of their recent gains 
as dealers reassessed the impact of the recent north sea oil rig 
explosion on petroleum supplies and prospects for an emergency opec 
meeting diminished 
it may be a case of calmer heads prevailing today peter 
beutel an oil analyst with elders futures inc said of fridays 
trading session 
prices for petroleum futures and contracts for refined products 
had soared on thursday as traders reacted to reports that the 
scotland rig explosion would affect about 12 percent of total north 
sea production or as much as 300000 barrels of oil per day 
in addition there was concern that the organization of 
petroleum exporting countries might call an emergency meeting to 
discuss overproduction among some of its members 
i think they overreacted to the effects of the platform fire 
and they realized it really didnt mean that much and the gains 
were given back said james r steele an energy analsyt with 
refco inc i think the market also realized there wasnt going to 
be an emergency meeting 
as a result he said fridays trading was highlighted by 
profittaking and a general correction from thursdays overbought 
condition 
